Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[We are told that about 50 cases of pneumonia are being reported among children, mainly in 2 elementary schools in the Wheeling, West Virginia Metropolitan Statistical Area, Marshall County, West Virginia, although additional cases are also being reported throughout the state. Patients are said to be school children with difficulty breathing, wheezing, lethargy, fever, and chest X-rays findings consistent with pneumonia. No further details about this outbreak are given in the news report above. The microbial etiology is as yet unknown.

Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) can be caused by a variety of microorganisms, including bacteria, viruses, and, less commonly, fungi. Viruses, such as influenza, can cause of outbreaks of CAP. Other viruses that cause CAP in school-aged children include adenovirus, parainfluenza virus, and rhinovirus capable (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/39/5/681.full.pdf). Respiratory syncytial virus and human metapneumovirus are more common in children under 5 years of age (http://reference.medscape.com/medline/abstract/15750086). Common bacterial causes of CAP in this age group include _Mycoplasma pneumoniae_, and _Chlamydia pneumoniae_. Outbreaks of CAP caused by _M. pneumoniae_ occur mostly in crowded environments, like households, schools, college dormitories, and military barracks, when coughing releases small droplets of respiratory secretions into the air that are inhaled by close contacts.

Fungi rarely cause pneumonia in otherwise healthy people, but outbreaks of CAP caused by environmental fungi that are characteristic of certain regions of the US, such as _Histoplasma_, _Coccidioides_, and _Blastomyces_, can occasionally occur, when soil harboring these fungi are disturbed. Although unlikely in elementary school children, the opioid epidemic in the US could also cause CAP as a result of aspiration of anaerobic bacterial mouth flora or as a result of injection drug use giving rise to hematogenous _Staphylococcus aureus_ pneumonia.

The Wheeling Metropolitan Statistical Area, with a population of a 147 950 residents in 2010, consists of 2 counties in the Northern Panhandle of West Virginia and one in eastern Ohio, anchored by the city of Wheeling, which is about 90 miles (about 145 km) southwest of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wheeling,_West_Virginia_metropolitan_area). A map of showing the location of Wheeling can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Wheeling,+WV+26003/Pittsburgh,+Pennsylvania.

Further information on the clinical, microbiologic, and epidemiologic characteristics of this outbreak would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources. - Mod.ML

